We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that relevant information is supplied and available to the intended users of the Financial Statements, enabling them to make well-informed decisions based on a comprehensive understanding of the financial reports. Also, conduct the following:
Make the necessary narrative disclosures as to the amount and nature of the cash and cash equivalents in Note 4;
Include in the NTFS disclosures on Biological Assets in compliance with IPSAS 27;
Promptly prepare and submit the necessary supporting schedules/attachments regarding financial liabilities, specifically the nature, character, composition/ breakdown, and date of incurrence of Accounts Payable and the disaggregated balances of the Deferred Real Property Tax and Special Education Tax (RPT/SET) Income Accounts to show the attributable amounts for taxpayers' advance payments, the accrued amount for the current year 2024, and the amount representing delinquencies; and
Include an additional disclosure on the breakdown of the prior period errors incurred and the nature of each error as well as amount of the correction for each financial statement line item affected in compliance with paragraph 54 of IPSAS 3.

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to direct:
the Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that all contracts entered into during the year are obligated in that year;
the Municipal Engineer to conduct mandatory inspection at year-end         with duly certified inspection reports in order to support the percentage of completion reported in the Status Report on Quarterly PPAs for all ongoing projects in order for the Municipal Accountant to accrue the same in the books; and
the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all total costs incurred for all projects, programs, and activities are accrued accordingly and that all commitments and obligations are completely and properly recognized in the SCBAA;
We also recommend that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to adjust the misstatements pertaining to the recorded capital outlay commitments by correcting the understated accounts payable amounting to ₱1,192,000.00 as supported by SWA or its equivalent at year-end.
Furthermore, direct the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to adjust their respective records by the following amounts to correctly reflect the Actual Amounts in the SCBAA:

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to instruct the following:
The Municipal Assessor, Municipal Accountant and Inventory Committee to reconcile their records pertaining to Land account. Determine the acquisition cost of each land parcel composing the Land account;
In cases where a parcel of land was acquired through a non-exchange transaction, such as donations, determine the prevailing fair market value at the date of acquisition;
The management to exhaust all possible means to document the legality of ownership of the lots through a Transfer Certificate of Title in the name of the Municipality as required under Sec. 39 (2) of PD No. 1445 and Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386;
Require the Municipal Assessor to request from the competent authority to appraise the properties without assigned costs so that these could be recorded properly in the books of accounts of the Municipality to fairly present the Land account in the financial statements;
For the Municipal Accountant to record the following suggested journal/ adjusting entries after the cost, the FMV of the land was identified:
To record the cost of Land based on traced acquisition cost (for purchased land)/ FMV (for Land received through donation) from the Assessor’s Office
Land				xxx
Prior Year’s Adjustment				xxx

We have recommended the Local Chief Executive to:

Create an Inventory Committee that has adequate personnel and at least one representative from the Accounting Unit and the Supply Unit of the LGU who will conduct annual physical count of PPE;



Establish sufficient policies and procedures in conducting the physical count, in coordination with the Supply Unit, Inventory Committee, Accounting Unit and other key personnel;



Instruct the Supply Unit to create and maintain its separate records of PPE items owned by the LGU and update the same every time there is a transaction or movement of PPE accounts;



Upon creation of an Inventory Committee, it shall conduct physical count of PPE at least annually together with a COA representative, who will witness the inventory-taking, and to prepare the RPCPPE which shall be submitted to the Auditor’s Office not later than January 31 of each year; and

Direct the Accounting and Supply Units to reconcile the PPE account balances based on their respective reports/records at the end of each year to ascertain that all properties owned by the LGU are duly accounted for.

We have recommended the Management to advise: 

Collecting Officers to reconcile the actual amount of daily collections with the individual receipts issued before recording in the Report of Collections and Deposits to ensure that all collections will be accounted accurately and remitted intact; 



Municipal Treasurer to verify the accuracy of the Report of Collections and Deposits and deposit all collections daily and intact;

The Treasury Office and Accounting Office to regularly reconcile their respective records to reflect only the exact amount of collections and deposits; and

Petty Cash Custodian to account the cash on hand and the actual expenses before refunding any unutilized balance to prevent abnormal balance.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management advise:
Collecting Officers to reconcile the actual amount of daily collections with the individual receipts issued before recording in the Report of Collections and Deposits to ensure that all collections will be accounted accurately and remitted intact;
Municipal Treasurer to verify the accuracy of the Report of Collections and Deposits and deposit all collections daily and intact;
The Treasury Office and Accounting Office to regularly reconcile their respective records to reflect only the exact amount of collections and deposits; and
Petty Cash Custodian to account the cash on hand and the actual expenses before refunding any unutilized balance to prevent abnormal balance.

We reiterated the following recommendations to Management:

To reconcile the records pertaining to the unremitted contributions and loan repayments and to effect immediately the remittance of long overdue accounts, if any; 

	To remit intact all GSIS contributions and loan amortizations on or before the 10th day of the following month to ensure that officials and employees enjoy the GSIS benefits to the maximum and as well as to avoid incurrence of penalties.

