To remit intact all GSIS contributions and loan amortizations on or before the 10th day of the following month to ensure that officials and employees enjoy the GSIS benefits to the maximum and as well as to avoid incurrence of penalties.

We recommended that Management strengthen the GAD Focal Point System of the LGU by:
(a)	Providing enough proficient personnel to support the Focal Person;
(b)	Require the Focal Person together with her team to: (a) develop and maintain GAD database containing gender statistics and sex-disaggregated data, gathered systematically, among the LGU population and clients; (b) regularly update these data; (c) conduct gender analysis on these data for planning, programming and policy formulation; (d) implement the identified PPAs; and (e) closely monitor the progress of activities to meet the objectives and realize the performance indicators and targets;
(c)	Ensure that the gender issues are clearly stated in the GAD Plan and design and formulate its PPAs according to the specific identified gender issues to address and resolve the same, supported with valid analyses.

6.13.	We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the members of the BAC to equip and update themselves of the existing GPPB guidelines which are exempted from the provisions of RA No. 9184 in response to COVID-19 outbreak;
Require the accounting office to submit immediately the Omnibus Sworn Statement and any of those mentioned in Item 5 of GPPB Circular No. 01-2020, whichever is applicable;
Require the Budget Office to submit the necessary approved APP;
Require the BAC to furnish COA of the Notices of Award and ensure the posting of the approved APP and NOAs and POs for these transactions.

We recommended that:
The accounting, budget and LDRRM offices to keep abreast with the rules and regulations on the disbursement of the LDRRMF and be mindful of Section 4, items 1 and 6 of the PD 1445;
The Sanggunian Bayan to keep up on the rules and regulations on the LDRRMF utilizations as well as on their powers and limitations as a council.

We recommended and the following LGU personnel agreed that:

1	The Chairperson of the MPIADC to initiate the planning and conduct comprehensive periodic physical inventory of ALL the supplies and property of the LGU as mandated in Section 124 of the NGAS Manual.  Prepare and submit also the RPCI as a result of the inventory taking of the supplies.  The RPCPPE and RPCI shall be reconciled with the accounting records.  These Reports shall also be submitted to COA pursuant to Section 124 of NGAS Manual for LGU;

2	The Chairperson of the MPIADC to ensure that all supplies in the RPCI and PPEs in the RPCPPE should contain complete information/identification, like item description, date acquired, serial numbers, property tags, cost, etc.  These data would be helpful in identifying and comparing the properties between records.  These information can be sourced from the previous years’ records and from the physical markings of the property.  Get the service of an in-house or independent appraiser, or the appraiser from the province, to provide cost of the properties with deficient documents;

3	The Property Custodian to make and maintain a list of all the supplies and property of the LGU, with complete information thereof reflected therein.  Ensure the ALL property of the LGU shall be counted and considered in the Report/list.  The list shall be reconciled with the similar records in the accounting at least a quarter;

4	The Municipal Accountant to maintain Supplies, PPEs and other property Ledger Cards, as well as complete list/schedule of the same.  Again, the supplies and property in the list/schedule should bear complete information as to description and specification.  Reconcile the accounting records with the list/reports being kept by the Property Custodian or with the MPIADC at least quarterly;

5	The GSO to property tag every PPE.  This will help in easy and fast monitoring of the assets and identification thereof in case a loss of the same;

6	The Property Custodian to provide PAR to every PPE issued to respective end users.  Accountability to the property redounds to the latter; and

7	The Management to adhere to Sections 119, 120 and 124 of the NGAS Manual, Volume 1, Section 3(c), Chapter   V   of   the   Manual   on   Property Custodianship, paragraph 13 of IPSAS No. 17, and other pertinent laws, rules and regulations governing the conduct of comprehensive physical count of supplies and properties, maintenance of records and submission of reports thereof to the Auditor.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:

1	Exert more effort to dig up available records and substantiate the balances which are absent of the same, as well as those claims which are deficient of supporting documents.  Ask assistance from the previous LGU accountant for the purpose.  Amounts which cannot be substantiated, despite enormous effort to do so, and which are not subject of the demand for payment shall be closed to Equity account;

2	Inquire, through a letter, from the LGU officers and employees, as well as those from the other creditors like the QUEDANCOR, LBP, DBP, and BAUG CARP, the existence and validity of the respective claims.  If the liabilities exist and valid, pay them.  If not, close the amount to Equity account;

3	Recheck available supporting documents for the accounts with negative balances.  Rectify immediately if there were errors noted in the recording of transactions. Collect from the creditors if there proved to be overpayments.  Again, amounts which cannot be substantiated, despite enormous effort to do so, shall be closed to Equity account; and

4	Adhere to Sections 4.8, 111.1 and 112 of P.D. No. 1445, as well as paragraph 7 of IPSAS No. 1 in the recognition, recording and reporting of the Due to Officers and Employees, Due to Other NGAs, Due to LGUs and Other Payables accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the following LGU personnel agreed that:

1	The Market Committee, through its Chairman, adjudicate all matters concerning the market based on the provisions of the Market Code.  Submit written suggestion or formulate procedures to observe with regard to the grant of installments covering the fees being imposed in the provisions of the Code.  These procedures shall include controls that ensure collection of the receivables.  The LEIPO must assist the Committee on this matter.  Submit the same to the Mayor and to the SB for necessary amendments to the Market Code;

2	The Market Committee to submit recommendations for appropriate consideration to the Mayor and to the SB concerning the obligatory fees that were found onerous by the vendors and for the latter to study thereof and to make amendments if necessary;

3	The Market Committee to immediately issue a Certificate of Award to the market vendors who have found qualified to own a respective stall in the market;

4	The Market Supervisor to secure copies of the Application to Lease the Market Stall and the Contract of Lease that are still on hand of the market vendors and to make sure that the complete data and information of all the stall holders are maintained;

5	The Municipal Accountant to recognize in the books as receivable the earned goodwill, occupancy privilege fee and block rental fee that were remained unsettled as of December 31, 2019 in the total amount of ₱1,449,200.00;

6	The Municipal Treasurer to adopt procedures ensuring the collection of the monthly goodwill, occupancy privilege fee and block rental fee. The LEIPO may assist the Treasurer in the formulation of the said procedures;

7	The Municipal Treasurer to provide a job order to collect minimal fees from the CR users or the duty to be added to the responsibilities being performed by the existing personnel assigned in the market;

8	The Market Committee to adjudicate every violation committed by the vendors and to impose corresponding penalty; and

9	Adhere to pertinent provisions covering the operations of the public market.

We recommended that:

13.7.1	The Sangguniang Bayan, with the inputs from the MSWDO, revise the Municipal Ordinance No. 003 series of 2018 to come up with a set of detailed and comprehensive guidelines on the budgeting, utilization and reporting of the fund allocated for the program. The Ordinance must include the legal basis of the program, the objectives thereof, the complete requirements as to who and how to avail the skolaran which includes residence of the recipient, social classification, annual income, course to take if in college, etc.  This likewise states the information on the responsibilities of the LGU in granting the educational assistance, responsibilities of the recipient for the amount received which include the grade to maintain, documents to present as proof of exemplary performance, etc., and the procedures to take if any party in the agreement is at fault to any of the provisions;

13.7.2	The Municipal Mayor, with the authority from the Sangguniang Bayan and assistance from the MSWDO, execute a MOA and enter into an agreement with each of the scholars so that the funds are safeguarded against misuse and to remind each party of the duties and responsibilities attached to the grant;

13.7.3	The MSWDO to furnish COA the list of LGU scholars detailing their basic biological information and other facts in compliance to the requirements set forth in Section 447(5)(xi) of R.A. No. 7160 and MO No. 003 series of 2018;

13.7.4	The Municipal Mayor, Accountant and MSWDO to submit to the Auditor justification on the payments of tuition and other fees to Mr. Bustillo and not the monthly ₱700.00 allowance as stated in the Ordinance.  Non-compliance hereof, or after evaluation by this end of the submitted justification and the same was found wanting of merit, this may result to suspension or disallowance of the amount as circumstances may warrant; and

13.7.5	The Management faithfully adhere to the intent of Section 447(5)(xi) of R.A No. 7160, Section 2 of P.D. No. 1445 and with the Municipal Ordinance No. 003 series of 2018 in the implementation of the Skolaran Program.

